---
import { getEntry, getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '~/components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import ListingCard from '~/components/ListingCard.astro';
import Callout from '~/components/Callout.astro';
import AuthorByline from '~/components/AuthorByline.astro';
import { article, breadcrumbList, place } from '~/lib/schema';
import { SITE_URL } from '~/lib/site';
import { crumb } from '~/lib/nav';

const dales = await getEntry('regions', 'yorkshire-dales');
if (!dales) throw new Error('Yorkshire Dales region entry missing — check src/content/regions/yorkshire-dales.md');

const allListings = await getCollection('listings', (e) => e.data.region === 'yorkshire-dales');
const featuredOrder = [
  'yorkshire-dales/miss-burrows-house',
  'yorkshire-dales/swale-view',
  'yorkshire-dales/low-mill-cottage',
];
const featured = featuredOrder
  .map((id) => allListings.find((l) => l.id === id))
  .filter((c): c is NonNullable<typeof c> => Boolean(c));

const cottageCount = 12;

const breadcrumbs = [
  crumb('Home', '/'),
  crumb('Yorkshire Dales', '/yorkshire-dales/'),
];

const pageUrl = '/yorkshire-dales/';
const pageTitle = dales.data.meta_title;
const pageDescription = dales.data.meta_description;

const jsonLd = [
  article({
    headline: 'Dog-friendly Yorkshire Dales: complete guide',
    description: pageDescription,
    image: new URL(dales.data.hero_image, SITE_URL).toString(),
    datePublished: '2026-06-18',
    url: pageUrl,
  }),
  place({
    name: dales.data.name,
    description: dales.data.description,
    image: new URL(dales.data.hero_image, SITE_URL).toString(),
  }),
  breadcrumbList(breadcrumbs),
];
---
<BaseLayout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} image={dales.data.hero_image} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-(--container-prose) px-6 py-12">
    <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} emitSchema={false} />

    <header class="mt-8 mb-8">
      <p class="eyebrow">Region</p>
      <h1 class="display mt-3">Dog-friendly Yorkshire Dales: complete guide</h1>
      <div class="mt-6">
        <AuthorByline />
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="aspect-[16/9] overflow-hidden bg-cream-soft border border-edge mb-10">
      <img src={dales.data.hero_image} alt="Limestone and drystone walls in the Yorkshire Dales" class="h-full w-full object-cover" loading="eager" />
    </div>

    <div class="prose-reading space-y-4 text-lg">
      <p>
        The Yorkshire Dales is walking country before it is anything else — limestone pavements and drystone walls, river valleys and high heather moor, threaded by one of the densest footpath networks in England. It sits right alongside the Lake District, and for a dog it's arguably the easier of the two: gentler underfoot, quieter, with the same depth of welcome in the cottages and an even stronger hand of walkers' pubs.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide leads with the cottages — twelve verified properties across Wharfedale, Wensleydale, Swaledale, Malhamdale, Ribblesdale and the Howgills, researched against the listing small print. River swimming spots and dog-friendly pubs follow. The Dales reward a particular kind of trip — walk from the door, paddle the dog in a river pool, end at a fire in a stone-flagged bar — and the whole guide is built around that.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <p class="eyebrow">Where to stay</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2">Cottages</h2>
      <p class="prose-reading mt-4">
        Twelve verified dog-friendly cottages, spread across all the main dales — stone villages, riverside, fellside and farmhouse. Each entry has the dog policy specifics — max dogs, pet supplement, garden status, what's actually provided — and editorial caveats baked in, including which gardens genuinely are (and aren't) enclosed.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
        {featured.map((c) => (
          <ListingCard listing={c} href={`/yorkshire-dales/cottages/#${c.id.split('/').pop()}`} />
        ))}
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8">
        <a href="/yorkshire-dales/cottages/" class="text-text">
          See all {cottageCount} dog-friendly cottages in the Yorkshire Dales →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <p class="eyebrow">On the water</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2">River swimming spots</h2>
      <p class="prose-reading mt-4">
        No coast, but river beaches, waterfall pools and a natural lake to swim a dog — and, unlike the seaside, no seasonal dog bans. Our guide covers the best spots with the real small print: water safety, flash floods, and the one stretch of river (the Strid) you must never let a dog near.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-8">
        <a href="/yorkshire-dales/beaches/" class="text-text">
          See dog-friendly swimming spots in the Yorkshire Dales →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <p class="eyebrow">After the walk</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2">Pubs</h2>
      <p class="prose-reading mt-4">
        From Britain's highest pub on Tan Hill to gas-lit village locals and smart gastro-inns by the river, the Dales do the dog-friendly walkers' pub as well as anywhere. Our guide leads with the pubs that take dogs throughout and notes which take them overnight.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-8">
        <a href="/yorkshire-dales/pubs/" class="text-text">
          See dog-friendly pubs in the Yorkshire Dales →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <p class="eyebrow">Editor's picks</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2">Best for…</h2>
      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
        <Callout eyebrow="Best for" title="A dog-led trip">
          <p>
            Swale View at Low Row is built around the dog — no limit on numbers, no pet charge, a genuinely dog-secure garden over the Swale, and the Swale Trail from the door. The rare cottage that puts the dog first.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3"><a href="/yorkshire-dales/cottages/#swale-view" class="text-text">See Swale View →</a></p>
        </Callout>
        <Callout eyebrow="Best for" title="The post-walk pint">
          <p>
            The Tan Hill Inn — Britain's highest pub, alone on the moor above Swaledale — takes dogs throughout, fire and all, and runs a proper dog menu. The walkers' pub by which others are judged.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3"><a href="/yorkshire-dales/pubs/#tan-hill-inn" class="text-text">See Tan Hill Inn →</a></p>
        </Callout>
        <Callout eyebrow="Best for" title="A gentle dog swim">
          <p>
            Semer Water, the largest of the Dales' two natural lakes, is shallow and current-free — the safest paddle on the list for a nervous or older dog, with a shore to run on. Keep them on a lead (it's a wildlife reserve).
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3"><a href="/yorkshire-dales/beaches/#semer-water" class="text-text">See Semer Water →</a></p>
        </Callout>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <h2>Travelling to the Yorkshire Dales with a dog</h2>
      <div class="prose-reading mt-6 space-y-4">
        <p>
          The Dales are an easy reach from both the M6 (west side — for Sedbergh, Ribblesdale and the western dales) and the A1 (east — for Wensleydale and Swaledale), with Skipton the usual southern gateway into Wharfedale. From the Midlands count two and a half to three hours, from the south four to five. Tebay and Killington Lake services on the M6 are the best dog stops on the western approach — Tebay especially, with its proper grass and farm-shop food.
        </p>
        <p>
          Once you're in, the thing to grasp is that the dales are largely dead-end valleys separated by high passes — so pick your dale and base yourself in it rather than planning to hop between them daily. The roads narrow fast to single-track between drystone walls, with sheep often on the carriageway on the open moor; take the passes (Buttertubs, Fleet Moss) gently with a dog aboard.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two practical notes. Sheep are everywhere and lambing runs roughly March to May, so a lead near livestock isn't optional — it's the law on access land in spring, and farmers here take it seriously. And Dales weather turns the rivers fast: a microfibre towel, a boot liner and an eye on the forecast save a lot of grief.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <h2>Adjacent regions</h2>
      <p class="prose-reading mt-4">
        The Yorkshire Dales pairs naturally with the <a href="/lake-district/" class="text-text">Lake District</a> immediately to the west — similar stone-and-slate cottage stock, the same dense footpath network, and the two regions almost touch at the Howgills, so a two-centre trip is easy. The <strong>North York Moors</strong> and the <strong>Yorkshire coast</strong> lie to the east for a contrast of heather moor and (seasonally dog-restricted) sands; both are in the queue for guide treatment.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16 border-t border-edge pt-12">
      <AuthorByline variant="full" />
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
